Carapace (
Figs. 13–15
) opaque to white, suboval in lateral view, surface with small to large pits and long setae (
Figs. 13A, B
), dorsally concave in center (less concave in ventral view) (
Fig. 13C
). Anterior margin rounded ventrally (
Figs. 13D, E
). Posterior margin rounded, ventrally with acute point. Margins without spines or tubercles. Greatest height near center. Carapace thin in dorsal view, navicular shape, with maximum width near center, margins slightly pointed at ends. LV more concave than RV dorsally. LV protruding over RV at center in ventral view. In internal view (
Fig. 13F
), rounded tubercles present dorsally, calcified inner lamella wider anteriorly than posteriorly. LV overlapping RV on all margins (
Fig. 13G
). Uncalcified part wide (
Figs. 14A–D
). Inner list and groove absent. Five central muscle scars present.

Zenker’s organ (
Fig. 18A
): seven rows (5 + 2) of spines.

Female description
: Carapace similar to male.T1 with three unequally long and smooth apical setae (h1>h2>h3) (
Fig. 18C
). A2 with short seta-like G2 claw about 1/3 as long as G1 claw (
Fig. 18D
). Other parts of A2 similar to male. Genital organ simple, rounded (
Fig. 18E
). All other soft body parts similar to male.
